Course Completion Feasibility
An online learning platform offers numCourses courses labeled from 0 to numCourses - 1.
Some courses have prerequisites:
Each pair (a, b) means:

You must complete course b before taking course a
This creates a directed graph:

Edge: b → a
Your task is to determine whether it is possible to complete all courses.

This is possible only if there is no cycle in the dependency graph.

Input format :
First line: Integer numCourses → total number of courses
Second line: Integer p → number of dependency pairs
Next p lines: Each line contains two integers a b
Meaning: To take course a, you must first complete course b
Output format :
Print "Possible" if all courses can be completed
Print "Not Possible" otherwise
Code constraints :
1 ≤ numCourses ≤ 2000
0 ≤ p ≤ 5000
0 ≤ a, b < numCourses
All dependency pairs are unique
Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
3 2
1 0
2 0
Output 1 :
Possible
Input 2 :
5 4
1 0
2 1
3 2
1 3
Output 2 :
Not Possible


Solution:

// You are using GCC
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
    int n,m;
    cin>>n>>m;
    
    vector<vector<int>>adj(n);
    
    for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
        int u,v;
        cin>>u>>v;
        
        adj[v].push_back(u);
    }
    
    vector<int>indegree(n,0);
    
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        for(int nei:adj[i]){
            indegree[nei]++;
        }
    }
    
    queue<int>que;
    
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        if(indegree[i] == 0){
            que.push(i);
        }
    }
    
    int completed = 0;
    
    while(!que.empty()){
        int node = que.front();
        que.pop();
        
        
        completed++;
        
        for(int nei:adj[node]){
            indegree[nei]--;
            if(indegree[nei] == 0){
                que.push(nei);
            }
        }
    }
    
    if(completed == n){
        cout<<"Possible";
    }
    else
    {
        cout<<"Not Possible";
    }
}
